# api — MAX HTTP Server

The public-facing HTTP backend for MAX. A thin **Hono** server that exposes
the RAG pipeline (`@max/sandbox`) over HTTP. It owns transport concerns —
routing, request validation, CORS, error shaping, process lifecycle — and
delegates all retrieval/LLM logic to the sandbox package. Keep business logic
out of here; this layer stays thin.

## Stack

- TypeScript strict, ESM. Extends `../../tsconfig.base.json` (`moduleResolution: bundler`, `composite`).
- Node 20+, run with `tsx` in dev. `@hono/node-server` adapter (not edge/Workers).
- Hono 4 for HTTP, `zod` for request validation.
- Depends on `@max/sandbox` (workspace) for `rag` (`ask`), `db` (`query`, `closePool`), and `config`.

## Layout

```
src/
  index.ts            # entry — serve(app), graceful shutdown
  app.ts              # Hono app: CORS, route mounting, notFound, onError
  config.ts           # API env (PORT, ALLOWED_ORIGINS), frozen apiConfig
  routes/
    chat.ts           # POST /chat — validate, call ask(), shape response
    health.ts         # GET /health — DB ping (SELECT 1)
```

## Conventions

- **Relative imports use `.js` extensions** (`./app.js`, `./config.js`) — TS rootDir is `src`, output is ESM. Cross-package imports use subpath exports (`@max/sandbox/rag`).
- Each route is its own `new Hono()` exported as a named `*Route`, mounted in `app.ts` via `app.route("/path", ...)`. One file per route group.
- **Validate all input with zod** at the top of the handler. On failure return `400` with `{ error, details: parsed.error.flatten() }`. Parse JSON in a try/catch and return `400 { error: "Invalid JSON body" }` on failure.
- **Never leak internals.** Per-route `try/catch` logs the real error (`console.error`) and returns a generic message (e.g. `500 { error: "Failed to generate answer" }`). The app-level `onError` in `app.ts` is the final backstop — keep it returning a generic 500.
- Responses are always `c.json(...)`. Map sandbox results to an explicit response shape (see `chat.ts`) — don't spread internal objects straight to the client.
- Named exports only, functions over classes, `async/await`.

## Config & env

- `config.ts` imports `@max/sandbox/config` **first** — that triggers dotenv loading the root `.env` and validates `DATABASE_URL` / `PORTKEY_API_KEY` at startup. Keep that import at the top.
- API-specific vars: `PORT` (default 8000, validated as a real port) and `ALLOWED_ORIGINS` (comma-separated, `*` = any). Read them only in `config.ts`; export via the frozen `apiConfig` so config is the single source of truth.
- No `.env` lives in this package — it's the root `.env` (copy from root `.env.example`).

## Lifecycle

- `index.ts` starts the server and registers `SIGINT`/`SIGTERM` handlers that close the HTTP server then `closePool()` from `@max/sandbox/db`. Preserve the idempotent `shuttingDown` guard and pool cleanup when editing startup.

## Current behavior to preserve

- `/chat` response shape: `{ answer, sources, wasRefused, retrievalScoreTop, logId, retrieval, minScoreUsed }`. All fields are additive over time — `logId` (best-effort observability) and the debug pair `retrieval` / `minScoreUsed` (D1) were added without changing prior fields. `retrieval` is the full top-K retrieval set (`RetrievalDebugItem[]` from `@max/sandbox/rag`: source/title/chunkIndex/score/headingPath?/contentPreview/passedThreshold) and is **always populated, including on refusal** — it exists so the eval harness can see found chunks + scores when MAX refuses, to calibrate `minScore`. `minScoreUsed` is the threshold those `passedThreshold` flags were computed against. These are distinct from `sources` (chunks the answer actually used), which stays `[]` on refusal — don't conflate them. Widget consumption of the debug fields is a separate step (D2). The threshold itself is sourced from sandbox config: `ask()` uses `options.minScore ?? config.refusalMinScore`, where `refusalMinScore` reads the optional `REFUSAL_MIN_SCORE` env var (finite, in `[0,1]`, default `0.55`, validated/fail-fast in `@max/sandbox/config`). It's tuned per embedding model and set in Railway (no rebuild) — so `minScoreUsed` reflects that configured value when no per-call override is passed.
- `/chat` is **single-turn**: it picks the last `user` message and ignores history. Don't quietly switch to multi-turn without flagging it.
- CORS is intentionally permissive (`cors()`) for dev; tightening it (using `apiConfig.allowedOrigins`) is a planned step — note it, don't silently rewire.

## Commands

Run from `packages/api/` (or via pnpm filter from the repo root):

- `pnpm dev` — `tsx watch src/index.ts` (hot reload)
- `pnpm build` — `tsc --build`
- `pnpm start` — `node dist/index.js`
- `pnpm typecheck` — `tsc --noEmit`
- `pnpm clean` — remove `dist` + build info

## Things not to do

- Don't put RAG/DB/LLM logic in routes — call into `@max/sandbox`. This layer is transport only.
- Don't read `process.env` outside `config.ts`.
- Don't return raw errors or stack traces to clients.
- Don't skip zod validation on request bodies.
- Don't drop `.js` extensions on relative imports — the build will break.
- Don't add new dependencies without flagging it — see the root rule.
